03710nam a22006015i 9780292761438DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211998txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927614387 a10.7560/7281102doi  a(DE-B1597)588038  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aQH541.5.M3bG65 1998 7aNAT0110002bisacsh04a577.68/09763/512211 aGomez, Gay M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Wetland Biography :bSeasons on Louisiana’s Chenier Plain /cGay M. Gomez. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1998  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. Comprehending the Complete Wetland -- t2. Chenier Journeys -- t3. Cycles and Seasons -- t4. Alligators -- t5. Waterfowl -- t6. Furbearers -- t7. Fisheries -- t8. Wetlands, Wildlife, and People -- tAppendix 1. Common Fauna and Flora of the Louisiana Chenier Plain -- tAppendix 2. Alligator Research Conducted at Rockefeller Wildlife Refuge -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLouisiana's Chenier Plain is a 2,200-square-mile region of marshes and oak-covered ridges (cheniers) that stretches along the Gulf of Mexico from Sabine Lake to Vermilion Bay. Its inhabitants, some 6,000 people of Cajun and other ancestries, retain strong economic and cultural ties to the land and its teeming wildlife. They call it paradise.but it is a vulnerable paradise. In this multifaceted study, Gay Gomez explores the interaction of the land, people, and wildlife of the Chenier Plain, revealing both the uniqueness of the region and the challenges it faces. After describing the geography and history of the Chenier Plain, Gomez turns to the lifeways of its people. Drawing on their words and stories, she tells how the chenier dwellers combine modern occupations with traditional pursuits such as alligator and waterfowl hunting, fur trapping, and fishing. She shows how these traditions of wildlife use provide both economic incentives for conservation and a source of personal and place identity. This portrait of a "working wetland" reveals how wildlife use and appreciation can give rise to a stewardship that balances biological, economic, and cultural concerns in species and habitat protection.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aChenier plainszLouisiana. 0aWetland conservationzLouisiana. 0aWetland ecologyzLouisiana. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292761438423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292761438/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK